Home Depot Product Search Relevance

Submitted by: Itay Bouganim and Ido Rom

Problem Statement

Shoppers rely on Home Depots product authority to find and buy the latest products and to get timely solutions to their home improvement needs. From installing a new ceiling fan to remodeling an entire kitchen, with the click of a mouse or tap of the screen, customers expect the correct results to their queries quickly. Speed, accuracy and delivering a frictionless customer experience are essential.

Task Description

Home Depot is asking to help them improve their customers' shopping experience by developing a model that can accurately predict the relevance of search results. Search relevancy is an implicit measure Home Depot uses to gauge how quickly they can get customers to the right products. Currently, human raters evaluate the impact of potential changes to their search algorithms, which is a slow and subjective process. By removing or minimizing human input in search relevance evaluation, Home Depot hopes to increase the number of iterations their team can perform on the current search algorithms.

Preface

Task goal: Finding the relevance value of the connection between a search phrase and a product description in a hardware store website.

In the following sections we are going to train multiple Siamese LSTM based networks with the goal of determining the relevance value for each product according to the search term and product description.
At first we are going to perform our task at a character based level, meaning that every search term/product description will be tokenized and represented as a sequence of numeric character representations.
In the second stage we will produce a network on a word level, each search term/product description will be represented as a tokenized sequence of preprocessed numeric words representation.
We will also using embedding in the second stage in order to produce a vectorized representation for every tokenized word in our corpus.

1.a. Character Level LSTM Model Preprocess

Character Tokenization

Character Tokenization splits apiece of text into a set of characters.

Character Tokenizers handles OOV words coherently by preserving the information of the word.
It breaks down the OOV word into characters and represents the word in terms of these characters.
It also limits the size of the vocabulary.

Drawbacks of Character Tokenization

Character tokens solve the OOV problem but the length of the input and output sentences increases rapidly as we are representing a sentence as a sequence of characters.
As a result, it becomes challenging to learn the relationship between the characters to form meaningful words.

from keras.preprocessing.text import Tokenizer

def create_char_tokenizer(corpus):
    tokenizer = Tokenizer(char_level=True)
    tokenizer.fit_on_texts(corpus)
    return tokenizer

def get_max_min_mean_len(col, df):
    l = np.array([len(c) for c in df[col]])
    return np.max(l), np.min(l), np.mean(l)

from keras.preprocessing.sequence import pad_sequences

data_cols = ['search_term', 'product_description']
cols = ['search_term', 'product_description', 'relevance']
padding_max_lens = {'search_term': max_search_term_train, 'product_description': math.trunc(mean_desc_train)}

def create_padded_sequences(df, tokenizer, padding_max_lens):
    df = df[cols].copy()
    for col in [col for col in cols if col != 'relevance']:
        sequences = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences(df[col])
        padded_sequences = pad_sequences(sequences, maxlen=padding_max_lens[col], padding='post', truncating='post')
        df[col] = padded_sequences.tolist()
    df['relevance'] = df['relevance'].apply(normalize_relevance)
    return df

from keras.preprocessing.sequence import pad_sequences
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

def extract_np_arrays(col, extract):
    return np.array([np.array(x) for x in col.to_numpy()]) if extract else col.to_numpy()

def create_X_y_splits(X_train_df, X_test_df, extract=True):
    X_train_df, X_valid_df, y_train, y_valid = train_test_split(X_train_df[data_cols], X_train_df.relevance, test_size=0.2)
    X_test_df, y_test = X_test_df[data_cols], X_test_df.relevance
    X_train = {'search': extract_np_arrays(X_train_df['search_term'], extract), 'desc': extract_np_arrays(X_train_df['product_description'], extract)}
    X_valid = {'search': extract_np_arrays(X_valid_df['search_term'], extract), 'desc': extract_np_arrays(X_valid_df['product_description'], extract)}
    X_test = {'search': extract_np_arrays(X_test_df['search_term'], extract), 'desc': extract_np_arrays(X_test_df['product_description'], extract)}
    return X_train, y_train.to_numpy(), X_valid, y_valid.to_numpy(), X_test, y_test.to_numpy()

In [25]:
def plot_history(history, plot_title, metrics):
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=len(metrics), figsize=(len(metrics) * 6, 4))
    
    # Plot training & validation accuracy values
    for i, metric in enumerate(metrics):
        axes[i].plot(history[metric])
        axes[i].plot(history[f'val_{metric}'])
        axes[i].legend(['Train', 'Validation'], loc='upper right')
        axes[i].set_title(f'Model {metric.replace("_metric", "").upper()} Metric')
        axes[i].set_ylabel(metric.upper())
        axes[i].set_xlabel('Epoch')
        axes[i].grid()

    fig.suptitle(plot_title + " Metrics History", y=1.05)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

import keras.backend as K

def root_mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred):
    return K.sqrt(K.mean(K.square(y_pred - y_true)))

To determine each model output vector semantic meaning simillarity we will put them through the defined similarity function (below)

In [28]:
def exponent_neg_manhattan_distance(left, right):
    ''' Helper function for the similarity estimate of the LSTMs outputs'''
    return K.exp(-K.sum(K.abs(left - right), axis=1, keepdims=True))

from keras.models import Model
from keras.layers import Input, LSTM, Lambda, Dense, Dropout
from keras.optimizers import Adadelta, Adam
from tensorflow.keras.utils import plot_model

def siamese_model(input_shape, name):
    inp = Input(shape=input_shape)
    x = LSTM(128, dropout=0.2, return_sequences=True)(inp)
    x = Dropout(0.2)(x)
    x = LSTM(128, dropout=0.2,)(x)
    return Model(inputs=inp, outputs=x, name=name)

ex_siamese_model = siamese_model((X_train['search'].shape[1], 1), 'Example Siamese Model')
ex_siamese_model.summary()

def create_char_siamese_model():
    search_inp = Input(shape=(X_train['search'].shape[1], 1))
    desc_inp = Input(shape=(X_train['desc'].shape[1], 1))
    search_model = siamese_model(input_shape=(X_train['search'].shape[1], 1), name='search_siamese')(search_inp)
    desc_model = siamese_model(input_shape=(X_train['desc'].shape[1], 1), name='description_siamese')(desc_inp)
    x = Lambda(function=lambda x: exponent_neg_manhattan_distance(x[0], x[1]))([search_model, desc_model])
    y = Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(x)
    
    model = Model([search_inp, desc_inp], y)
    model.compile(loss=root_mean_squared_error, optimizer='adam', metrics=['mse', 'mae', root_mean_squared_error])
    return model

siamese_char_seq_model = create_char_siamese_model()
siamese_char_seq_model.summary()

from keras.models import load_model
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error

def calculate_model_results(create_model_func, saved_model_name, X_test, X_train, X_valid, y_test, y_train, y_valid):
    model = create_model_func()
    model.load_weights(join(model_save_dir, f'model_{saved_model_name}.h5'))
    model_name = saved_model_name.replace('_', ' ').title()
    
    print('Test data results:')
    y_pred = model.predict((X_test['search'], X_test['desc']), verbose=1)
    print(f'{model_name} RMSE: {np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))}')
    print(f'{model_name} MSE: {mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)}')
    print(f'{model_name} MAE: {mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)}')
    save_results_dict({'Name': saved_model_name, 'MSE': mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred), 'MAE': mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred), 'RMSE':np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))})
    
    print('\nValidation data results:')
    y_pred = model.predict((X_valid['search'], X_valid['desc']), verbose=1)
    print(f'{model_name} RMSE: {np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_valid, y_pred))}')
    print(f'{model_name} MSE: {mean_squared_error(y_valid, y_pred)}')
    print(f'{model_name} MAE: {mean_absolute_error(y_valid, y_pred)}')
    
    print('\nTrain data results:')
    y_pred = model.predict((X_train['search'], X_train['desc']), verbose=1)
    print(f'{model_name} RMSE: {np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_train, y_pred))}')
    print(f'{model_name} MSE: {mean_squared_error(y_train, y_pred)}')
    print(f'{model_name} MAE: {mean_absolute_error(y_train, y_pred)}')

def create_char_siamese_joined_model():
    search_inp = Input(shape=(X_train['search'].shape[1], 1))
    desc_inp = Input(shape=(X_train['desc'].shape[1], 1))
    lstm1 = LSTM(128, dropout=0.2, return_sequences=True)
    x1 = lstm1(search_inp)
    x2 = lstm1(desc_inp)
    lstm2 = LSTM(128, dropout=0.2)
    x1 = lstm2(x1)
    x2 = lstm2(x2)
    x = Lambda(function=lambda x: exponent_neg_manhattan_distance(x[0], x[1]))([x1, x2])
    y = Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(x)
    
    model = Model([search_inp, desc_inp], y)
    model.compile(loss=root_mean_squared_error, optimizer='adam', metrics=['mse', 'mae', root_mean_squared_error])
    return model

Baseline Count Vectorizer model

As we have seen, In order to use textual data for predictive modeling, the text must be parsed to remove certain words this process is called tokenization.
These words need to then be encoded as integers, or floating-point values, for use as inputs in machine learning algorithms.
This process is called feature extraction (or vectorization).

Scikit-learns CountVectorizer is used to convert a collection of text documents to a vector of term/token counts.
It also enables the pre-processing of text data prior to generating the vector representation.
This functionality makes it a highly flexible feature representation module for text.

from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import CountVectorizer

def create_fit_count_vectorizer(corpus):
    count_vec = CountVectorizer(analyzer='char')
    count_vec.fit_transform(corpus)
    return count_vec

count_vec = create_fit_count_vectorizer(corpus)

def fit_to_count_vec(df, count_vec=count_vec):
    return np.squeeze(count_vec.transform(df).toarray())

def create_count_vectorizer_X_y(train, test):
    X_train_df, X_valid_df, y_train, y_valid = train_test_split(train[data_cols], train.relevance.apply(normalize_relevance), test_size=0.2)
    X_test_df, y_test = test[data_cols], test.relevance.apply(normalize_relevance)
    X_train = {'search': fit_to_count_vec(X_train_df['search_term']), 'desc': fit_to_count_vec(X_train_df['product_description'])}
    X_valid = {'search': fit_to_count_vec(X_valid_df['search_term']), 'desc': fit_to_count_vec(X_valid_df['product_description'])}
    X_test = {'search': fit_to_count_vec(X_test_df['search_term']), 'desc': fit_to_count_vec(X_test_df['product_description'])}

    return X_train, y_train, X_valid, y_valid, X_test, y_test

def benchmark_siamese_model(input_shape, name):
    inp = Input(shape=input_shape)
    x = Dense(512, activation='relu')(inp)
    x = Dense(256, activation='relu')(x)
    return Model(inputs=inp, outputs=x, name=name)

benchmark_ex_siamese_model = benchmark_siamese_model(X_train_cv['search'].shape[1], 'Example Benchamrk Siamese Model')

def create_benchmark_char_siamese_model(count_vec_size):
    search_inp = Input(shape=count_vec_size)
    desc_inp = Input(shape=count_vec_size)
    search_model = benchmark_siamese_model(input_shape=count_vec_size, name='search_siamese')(search_inp)
    desc_model = benchmark_siamese_model(input_shape=count_vec_size, name='description_siamese')(desc_inp)
    x = Lambda(function=lambda x: exponent_neg_manhattan_distance(x[0], x[1]))([search_model, desc_model])
    y = Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(x)
    
    model = Model([search_inp, desc_inp], y)
    model.compile(loss=root_mean_squared_error, optimizer='adam', metrics=['mse', 'mae', root_mean_squared_error])
    return model

def fe_ml_model_scores(model_name, ml_model, fe_model):
    preds = fe_model.predict((X_test['search'], X_test['desc']), verbose=1)
    print('Test data results:')
    y_pred = ml_model.predict(preds)
    print(f'{model_name} RMSE: {np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))}')
    print(f'{model_name} MSE: {mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)}')
    print(f'{model_name} MAE: {mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)}')
    save_results_dict({'Name': model_name, 'MSE': mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred), 'MAE': mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred), 'RMSE':np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))})
    
    preds = fe_model.predict((X_valid['search'], X_valid['desc']), verbose=1)
    print('\nValidation data results:')
    y_pred = ml_model.predict(preds)
    print(f'{model_name} RMSE: {np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_valid, y_pred))}')
    print(f'{model_name} MSE: {mean_squared_error(y_valid, y_pred)}')
    print(f'{model_name} MAE: {mean_absolute_error(y_valid, y_pred)}')
    
    preds = fe_model.predict((X_train['search'], X_train['desc']), verbose=1)
    print('\nTrain data results:')
    y_pred = ml_model.predict(preds)
    print(f'{model_name} RMSE: {np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_train, y_pred))}')
    print(f'{model_name} MSE: {mean_squared_error(y_train, y_pred)}')
    print(f'{model_name} MAE: {mean_absolute_error(y_train, y_pred)}')

def word_frequency_count(corpus, split=True):
    from collections import defaultdict

    word_freq = defaultdict(int)
    for sent in corpus:
        for i in sent.split() if split else sent:
            word_freq[i] += 1
    return word_freq, len(word_freq)

Word preprocessing

Tokenization

We will use punctuation tokenization in order to remove any punctuation symbols (e.g. . , ! ( )) From the individual words.
This will help us reduce the word count in our corpus and will also cause simillar words have the same tokenized value (e.g. doors, doors. and doors will all be tokenized as doors).

Lowercasing:

This is the simplest technique of text preprocessing which consists of lowercasing every single token of the input text.
It helps in dealing with sparsity issues in the dataset.
For example, a text is having mixed-case occurrences of the token Canada, i.e., at some places token canada is and in other Canada is used.

Stop-word removal:

Stop-words are commonly used words in a language. Examples are a, an, the, is, what etc.
Stop-words are removed from the text so that we can concentrate on more important words and prevent stop-words from being analyzed.
If we search what is text preprocessing, we want to focus more on text preprocessing rather than what is.

Stemming:

Stemming is the elementary rule-based process of removal of inflectional forms from a token.
The token is converted into its root form. For example, the word troubled is converted into trouble after performing stemming.

Lemmatization: (will not be used here)

Lemmatization is similar to stemming, the difference being that lemmatization refers to doing things properly with the use of vocabulary and morphological analysis of words, aiming to remove inflections from the word and to return the base or dictionary form of that word, also known as the lemma.
It does a full morphological analysis of the word to accurately identify the lemma for each word.

from nltk.stem.porter import PorterStemmer
from nltk.stem import WordNetLemmatizer
from nltk.tokenize import word_tokenize
from nltk.corpus import stopwords

ps = PorterStemmer()
wml = WordNetLemmatizer()
Stopwords = set(stopwords.words('english'))

def cleaning_sentence(sentence):
    sentence_tokens = word_tokenize(sentence)
    cleaned_sentence = []
    for word in sentence_tokens:
        # Use only words, character combinations and numbers 
        if (not word.isalpha() and not word.isnumeric()) and len(word) == 1: 
            continue
        word = word.lower() # Lower case word
        if word in Stopwords: # Remove stop words
            continue
        stem_word = ps.stem(word) # Stem word
        cleaned_sentence.append(stem_word)
    return cleaned_sentence

print('Cleaned output should contain only words, numbers and character combinations.\nSingle characters (e.g. . , ( )) should be removed.')
print(cleaning_sentence("Hello World, 2 90 #SC (i am just checking how the 3/4 cleaning process work; random words: walk, talking, sitting, sat)."))

2.b. Create word embedding vectors

We will use word2vec model in order to produce vectorized representation for every word in out preprocesses corpus.

Word2Vec

Word2vec is a technique for natural language processing.
The word2vec algorithm uses a neural network model to learn word associations from a large corpus of text.
Once trained, such a model can detect synonymous words or suggest additional words for a partial sentence.
As the name implies, word2vec represents each distinct word with a particular list of numbers called a vector.
The vectors are chosen carefully such that a simple mathematical function (the cosine similarity between the vectors) indicates the level of semantic similarity between the words represented by those vectors.

from sklearn.manifold import TSNE

def plot_word2vec_model(n=100, model=word2vec_model):
    vocab = list(model.wv.vocab)[:n]
    X = model[vocab]
    tsne = TSNE(n_components=2)
    X_tsne = tsne.fit_transform(X)
    df = pd.DataFrame(X_tsne, index=vocab, columns=['x', 'y'])
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20,20))
    ax = fig.add_subplot(1, 1, 1)
    ax.scatter(df['x'], df['y'])
    
    for word, pos in df.iterrows():
        ax.annotate(word, pos)
    plt.show()

from keras.preprocessing.sequence import pad_sequences

cols = ['search_term', 'product_description', 'relevance']
padding_max_lens = {'search_term': max_search_term_train, 'product_description': math.trunc(mean_desc_train)}

def create_word_padded_sequences(df, tokenizer, padding_max_lens):
    df = df[cols].copy()
    for col in [col for col in cols if col != 'relevance']:
        sequences = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences([cleaning_sentence(c) for c in df[col]])
        padded_sequences = pad_sequences(sequences, maxlen=padding_max_lens[col], padding='post', truncating='post')
        df[col] = padded_sequences.tolist()
    df['relevance'] = df['relevance'].apply(normalize_relevance)
    return df

We will use cosine simillarity this time to measure simillarity:

Cosine Simillarity

Cosine similarity is a measure of similarity between two non-zero vectors of an inner product space.
It is defined to equal the cosine of the angle between them, which is also the same as the inner product of the same vectors normalized to both have length 1.

In [52]:
display_image('cosine.png')
In [41]:
from keras import backend as K

def cosine_distance(vests):
    x, y = vests
    x = K.l2_normalize(x, axis=-1)
    y = K.l2_normalize(y, axis=-1)
    return -K.mean(x * y, axis=-1, keepdims=True)

def cos_dist_output_shape(shapes):
    shape1, shape2 = shapes
    return (shape1[0],1)

For the word level model we will use Bidirectional LSTM with feed-forward to convolutional layer that will then produce a representation vector of size 128.

Bidirectional Recurrent Neural Networks

Bidirectional Recurrent Neural Networks (BRNN) connect two hidden layers of opposite directions to the same output.
With this form of generative deep learning, the output layer can get information from past (backwards) and future (forward) states simultaneously.

from keras.layers import Embedding, Conv1D, MaxPooling1D, Flatten, Concatenate, Dropout, GlobalAveragePooling1D, Bidirectional, Activation, Input, LSTM, Dense, Lambda
from keras.optimizers import Adadelta, Adam
from keras.models import Model
from tensorflow.keras.utils import plot_model
from keras.regularizers import l2 

def word_siamese_model(input_shape, name, embedding_dim, embedding_matrix):
    inp = Input(shape=input_shape, dtype='int32')
    x = Embedding(len(embedding_matrix), embedding_dim, weights=[embedding_matrix], input_length=input_shape, trainable=False)(inp)
    x = Bidirectional(LSTM(128, return_sequences=True))(x)
    x = Conv1D(filters=32, kernel_size=8, strides=1, activation='relu', padding='same')(x)
    x = MaxPooling1D(3)(x)
    x = Activation('relu')(x)
    x = Flatten()(x)
    x = Dense(128, activation='relu')(x)
    return Model(inputs=inp, outputs=x, name=name)

ex_siamese_model = word_siamese_model(X_train['search'].shape[1], 'Example Siamese Model', embedding_dim=embedding_dim, embedding_matrix=embedding_matrix)
ex_siamese_model.summary()

def create_word_siamese_model(embedding_dim, embedding_matrix):
    search_inp = Input(shape=X_train['search'].shape[1], dtype='int32')
    desc_inp = Input(shape=X_train['desc'].shape[1], dtype='int32')
    search_model = word_siamese_model(input_shape=X_train['search'].shape[1], name='search_siamese', 
                                      embedding_dim=embedding_dim, embedding_matrix=embedding_matrix)(search_inp)
    desc_model = word_siamese_model(input_shape=X_train['desc'].shape[1], name='description_siamese', 
                                    embedding_dim=embedding_dim, embedding_matrix=embedding_matrix)(desc_inp)
    malstm = Lambda(function=lambda x: exponent_neg_manhattan_distance(x[0], x[1]), output_shape=lambda x: (x[0][0], 1))([search_model, desc_model])
    cosine = Lambda(cosine_distance, output_shape=cos_dist_output_shape)([search_model, desc_model])
    conc = Concatenate(axis=-1)([malstm, cosine])
    x = Dense(100, activation="relu", name='conc_layer')(conc)
    x = Dropout(0.05)(x)
    y = Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(x)
    
    model = Model([search_inp, desc_inp], y)
    model.compile(loss=root_mean_squared_error, optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy', 'mse', 'mae', root_mean_squared_error])
    return model

siamese_word_seq_model = create_word_siamese_model(embedding_dim, embedding_matrix)
siamese_word_seq_model.summary()

Next we will try to train the same model for the two inputs so that the model share the trained weights for both inputs.

Working with same size words input vector

We will try making the two words input vectors (search terms and descriptions) the same length.
We will take the mean description word count as both vector length.

Increasing the Convolutional layers depth and working with common siamese layers

We will use common siamese models by using the same layers in order to share the layers weights.
Also, we will increase the convolutional layers depth and filters (the output from the biderectional LSTM will be the input for the convolution).

In [63]:
from keras.layers import Embedding, Conv1D, MaxPooling1D, Flatten, Concatenate, Dropout, Bidirectional, Activation, Input, LSTM, Dense, Lambda, GlobalMaxPooling1D
from keras.optimizers import Adadelta, Adam
from keras.models import Model
from tensorflow.keras.utils import plot_model
from keras.regularizers import l2 

def create_word_siamese_joined_model(embedding_dim, embedding_matrix):
    search_inp = Input(shape=X_train['search'].shape[1], dtype='int32')
    desc_inp = Input(shape=X_train['desc'].shape[1], dtype='int32')
    # Siamese model part with joined weights
    emb = Embedding(len(embedding_matrix), embedding_dim, weights=[embedding_matrix],
                    input_length=max([X_train['search'].shape[1], X_train['desc'].shape[1]]), trainable=False)
    search_emb = emb(search_inp)
    desc_emb = emb(desc_inp)
    lstm = Bidirectional(LSTM(128, return_sequences=True))
    x1 = lstm(search_emb)
    x2 = lstm(desc_emb)
    lstm2 = Bidirectional(LSTM(128, return_sequences=True))
    x1 = lstm2(x1)
    x2 = lstm2(x2)
    conv = Conv1D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, strides=1, activation='relu', padding='same')
    conv2 = Conv1D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, strides=1, activation='relu', padding='same')
    x1 = conv(x1)
    x2 = conv(x2)
    x1 = conv2(x1)
    x2 = conv2(x2)
    mx = MaxPooling1D(3)
    x1 = mx(x1)
    x2 = mx(x2)
    act = Activation('relu')
    x1 = act(x1)
    x2 = act(x2)
    flat = Flatten()
    x1 = flat(x1)
    x2 = flat(x2)
    d = Dense(128, activation='relu')
    x1 = d(x1)
    x2 = d(x2)
    # Output vector simillarity
    cosine = Lambda(cosine_distance, output_shape=cos_dist_output_shape)([x1, x2])
    y = Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(cosine)
    
    model = Model([search_inp, desc_inp], y)
    model.compile(loss=root_mean_squared_error, optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy', 'mse', 'mae', root_mean_squared_error])
    return model

siamese_word_seq_joined_model = create_word_siamese_joined_model(embedding_large_dim, embedding_matrix_large)

Suggestions for further improvement

We can suggest a few ways in order to improve our model and overcome the overfitting that occurs while training:

  • Classification instead of regression - since the relevance values (Y) are discrete in the range [1, 3] we could view the problem as a classification problem.
    Instead of trying to use regression to produce the relevance value associated with the search term and the description,
    we could try to classify the simillarity between them to one of the unique relevance values in out dataset.
  • Increase the representation of word/character vectors - we used the mean value of the word/charcter count as the size of the sentence representation vector in order to avoid exploding runtime.
    By doing that we may have lost information regarding the rest of the sentence for sentences that are longer than the mean value.
    We could represent all of the sentences as the maximum value or increase it to some value instead of the mean to avoid losing data.(down side is it will cause also for some sentences to have more zero padding at the end of each sentence, can cause the model to converge slower).
  • Use better/more suited tokenization and word processing methods - we used a pretty simplistic sentence/word tokenization techniques (stemming, lowercasing etc.)
    Going forawrd we could try and use tokenization techniques that take the context of the sentence into account in order to better determine simillarity.
    We could also try and explore tokenization without using lowercasing or with using lemmenization instead of stemming. Another options is to keep the stop words in our corpus to better preserve context. Maybe we should keep some of the punctuation in the sentence to preserve some of the original meaning of tokenize by spaces and not by punctuation alltogether. It is also a possibility that the preprocessing of the sentence was too aggresive due to the stemming and stop words removal proccess and this will result in a lower quality embedding since we lose some connections - we could try different types of sentence preprocessing.
  • Increase Embedding dimensions - We could try using an even larger word vector representation to preserve more sentence data con context in the embedding vectorized word representation.
  • Exploring better simillarity functions - We tried using two different simillarity functions (Exponent manhatten distance and Cosine simillarity).
    We could try and explore more simillarity metrics that may be better suited to our problem.
  • Networks architecture improvements suggestions -
    • Add LSTM hidden nodes to better preserve history.
    • Add Dense/Conv layers.
    • Add more dropout to avoid overfitting to training data.
    • Try different activations/loss functions (if converted to classification task we could use categorical crossentropy instead of RMSE and softmax activation on last layer instead of sigmoid).

Our Learning Process

In this assignment we learned how to use siamese networks in order to determine simillarity betweeen word/character sequences.
We learned how to perform two forms of word/character tokenization (by using the keras Tokenizer class and the CountVectorizer class).
We also learned how to perform text analysis, preprocessing(splitting, stemming and stop words removal) and using the word2vec models in order to create predefined embedding layers with vectorized representations for words in corpus.
We used feature extraction on pretrained models and combined them with a few ML algorithms such as XGBoost, CatBoost and Random Forests.
